				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lunardelta" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2898811); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2898811&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227484" alt="LunarDelta" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2898811)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lunardelta" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2898811); return false;" >LunarDelta</a></span> <span class="odate time_1583022113 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Mar 2020 00:21</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4524566">
									

<p>I saw that one on your Sandbox. I actually kind of liked it, TBH. I felt bad for the guy, but really can't condone his actions. As an O5 he should really be able to set aside his feelings, especially in the face of something as monstrous as 3125. I mean honestly, the chances his loved one isn't either dead or out disfiguring &quot;delightful people&quot; with the rest of the infected are practically zero.</p>
<p>Also, if there's not yet any SCP-3125 in this alternate reality, is it safe to assume there's probably no Fifthism, SCP-1425, Theta Prime or other related anomalies?</p>
<p>One final thought: It's been stated multiple times over the years that SCP-3125's origin, while ambiguous, is almost certainly much higher-dimensional. At least Marion thought so. If that <em>is</em> the case, then isn't it possible, perhaps even inevitable, that even with the infected universe sealed off, 3125 will find a way out eventually, perhaps even accidentally?</p>

							</div>

								
					
