					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lunardelta" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2898811); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2898811&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227484" alt="LunarDelta" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2898811)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/lunardelta" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2898811); return false;" >LunarDelta</a></span> <span class="odate time_1583023023 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">01 Mar 2020 00:37</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4524580">
									

<p>None of us really know much about the man at the end. He's called &quot;Red&quot; because that's the code name the Foundation gave him back when they still existed and before SCP-3125 manifested. He intentionally sacrificed/offered himself to 3125 knowing full well what the consequences would be, and became a sort of mouthpiece or spokesperson for it. According to agent Barsin (from <em>Ojai</em>) who tried to take on Red and failed miserably, it's almost impossible to determine where Red ends and 3125 begins. As for why he did this&#8230; I have no idea. Hopefully we will learn by the end.</p>
<p>This is pure speculation on my part, but I get the feeling that being merged with a human mind allows 3125 to behave much more intelligently and maliciously than it otherwise would be able to. (Not that 3125 isn't plenty malicious by itself, but it seems to be a kind of purposeless, omni-directional malice. Being attached to Red gives it <em>focus</em>.)</p>

							</div>

								
