					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/werdna" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2161854); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2161854&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227484" alt="werdna" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2161854)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/werdna" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2161854); return false;" >werdna</a></span> <span class="odate time_1583379770 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">05 Mar 2020 03:42</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4532086">
									

<p>It's funny. I was reading this with an extension, Dark Reader, turned on, and immediately saw the white monolith since the extension takes some liberties with changing the colors of webpage elements to create a dark theme on whatever page I'm viewing. I presumed that this was just an inverted element and that at the bottom of the story was just another black monolith, as seen in CASE HATE RED, but when I turned off Dark Reader it turned out it really was supposed to be white. So then I assumed that it was just some kind of dramatic padding for the page before &quot;To be concluded.&quot;</p>
<p>Afterwards, I came to the comments and now it all makes sense.</p>
<p>Personally, I would use a centered div element with a style tag setting the background color, and the height and width in pixels. As of my reading it, you used a character, the color of which was automatically changed by the extension to match the rest of the text.</p>

							</div>

								
